<font color="#FF0000">TO CHRIS AND KEITH</font><br>
<tt>Thu Mar 13  6:08:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Chris,<br><br>
Your comments to JJ are a good defense. You have spirit and conviction. That's good.<br><br>
Your observations of the Washington lobby hit the mark. Although I do not think influence pedling is a new phenomenon, as it has been going on since the founding of this country, it is acutely visible today. People are growing less tolerant of the &quot;traditional&quot; ways of the government doing business. I feel that is good. Pressure on the government to change some of its ways is also good. This is a dynamic country. The way things were in the 40's and 50's were no longer viable and were moved aside in the 60's and 70's. The process continues. We must keep our heads straight, however. <br><br>
The sale of arms is a symptom of a larger problem. When domestic lobbyists and agents of foreign powers have more access to our lawmakers than the constituents who elected them, we have a problem. That is what I feel needs changing.<br>
Our perspective is also skewed when laboratory animals receive, by law, better care than homeless citizens. The USDA inspects and enforces regulations in the interest of happy rabbits, but I continue to see homeless adults and children sleeping under bushes and in cars. This is another example of the effects of a lobbyist problem.<br><br>
I do not feel the characterization of the government as &quot;evil&quot; is entirely appropriate. I know we are discussing points on view and shades of gray, but I feel we must seek a different word.<br><br>
To Keith:<br><br>
Welcome. Your comments and honesty are appreciated. Many Vietnam Vets also agonized over how to avoid the war, or minimize its impact on us. I recall many endless discussions with my friends on this very issue. In the end, we all made choices that were right for us individually in the context of our circumstances and the times. I was caught up in the war and was well into it when the lottery appeared. I recall thinking of the news of it, and checking the number for my birthday. It was a very low number. I was destined to be where I was, anyway, in all eventuality. The lottery did send a message to the troops in Vietnam in spite of the propaganda machine. It was just another milestone in the decline of the morale and the increase in disobedience of the US Army soldiers. In retrospect, it seems that the soldiers eventually had their own internal protest of the war for some very good reasons. I could see it beginning while I was there.     
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


